# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gdpr-compliance
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The **Data Protection Directive,** officially Directive 95/46/EC, enacted in October 1995, was a European Union directive which regulated the processing of personal data within the European Union (EU) and the free movement of such data.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The Data Protection Directive was an important component of EU privacy and human rights law.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The principles set out in the Data Protection Directive were aimed at the protection of fundamental rights and freedoms in the processing of personal data.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The General Data Protection Regulation, adopted in April 2016, superseded the Data Protection Directive and became enforceable on 25 May 2018.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The right to privacy is a highly developed area of law in Europe.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] All the member states of the Council of Europe (CoE) are also signatories of the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR).
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] Article 8 of the ECHR provides a right to respect for one's "private and family life, his home and his correspondence", subject to certain restrictions.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The European Court of Human Rights has given this article a very broad interpretation in its jurisprudence.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] In 1973, American scholar Willis Ware published *Records, Computers, and the Rights of Citizens*, a report that was to be influential on the directions these laws would take.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] In 1980, in an effort to create a comprehensive data protection system throughout Europe, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) issued its "Recommendations of the Council Concerning Guidelines Governing the Protection of Privacy and Trans-Border Flows of Personal Data".
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] Accountability—data subjects should have a method available to them to hold data collectors accountable for not following the above principles.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The OECD Guidelines, however, were non-binding, and data privacy laws still varied widely across Europe.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The United States, meanwhile, while endorsing the OECD's recommendations, did nothing to implement them within the United States.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] However, the first six principles were incorporated into the EU Directive.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] In 1981, the Members States of the Council of Europe adopted the Convention for the Protection of Individuals with regard to Automatic Processing of Personal Data (Convention 108) to implement Article 8 of the ECHR.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] Convention 108 obliges the signatories to enact legislation concerning the automatic processing of personal data, and was modernised and reinforced in 2018 to become "Convention 108+".
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] In 1989 with German reunification, the data the East German secret police (Stasi) collected became well known, increasing the demand for privacy in Germany.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] At the time West Germany already had privacy laws since 1977 (*Bundesdatenschutzgesetz*).
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The European Commission realized that diverging data protection legislation amongst EU member states impeded the free flow of data within the EU and accordingly proposed the Data Protection Directive.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The directive regulates the processing of personal data regardless of whether such processing is automated or not.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] This definition is meant to be very broad.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] Data are "personal data" when someone is able to link the information to a person, even if the person holding the data cannot make this link.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] Some examples of "personal data" are: address, credit card number, bank statements, criminal record, etc.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The responsibility for compliance rests on the shoulders of the "controller", meaning the natural or artificial person, public authority, agency or any other body which alone or jointly with others determines the purposes and means of the processing of personal data (art.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The data protection rules are applicable not only when the controller is established within the EU, but whenever the controller uses equipment situated within the EU in order to process data.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] 4) Controllers from outside the EU, processing data in the EU, will have to follow data protection regulation.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] In principle, any online business trading with EU residents would process some personal data and would be using equipment in the EU to process the data (i.e. the customer's computer).
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] As a consequence, the website operator would have to comply with the European data protection rules.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The directive was written before the breakthrough of the Internet, and to date there is little jurisprudence on this subject.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] Personal data should not be processed at all, except when certain conditions are met.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] These conditions fall into three categories: transparency, legitimate purpose, and proportionality.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The data subject has the right to be informed when his personal data is being processed.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The controller must provide his name and address, the purpose of processing, the recipients of the data and all other information required to ensure the processing is fair.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] Data may be processed only if at least one of the following is true (art.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] Personal data can only be processed for specified explicit and legitimate purposes and may not be processed further in a way incompatible with those purposes.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] 6 b) The personal data must have protection from misuse and respect for the "certain rights of the data owners which are guaranteed by EU law".
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] Personal data may be processed only insofar as it is adequate, relevant and not excessive in relation to the purposes for which they are collected and/or further processed.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] Member States shall lay down appropriate safeguards for personal data stored for longer periods for historical, statistical or scientific use.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] When sensitive personal data (can be: religious beliefs, political opinions, health, sexual orientation, race, membership of past organisations) are being processed, extra restrictions apply.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The data subject may object at any time to the processing of personal data for the purpose of direct marketing.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] An algorithmic-based decision which produces legal effects or significantly affects the data subject may not be based solely on automated processing of data.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] 15) A form of appeal should be provided when automatic decision making processes are used.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] Each member state must set up a supervisory authority, an independent body that will monitor the data protection level in that member state, give advice to the government about administrative measures and regulations, and start legal proceedings when data protection regulation has been violated.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] 28) Individuals may lodge complaints about violations to the supervisory authority or in a court of law.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The controller must notify the supervisory authority before he starts to process data.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The notification contains at least the following information (art.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] This information is kept in a public register.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The Directive's Article 29 created the "Working party on the Protection of Individuals with regard to the Processing of Personal Data", commonly known as the "Article 29 Working Party".
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The Working Party gives advice about the level of protection in the European Union and third countries.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The Working Party negotiated with United States representatives about the protection of personal data, the Safe Harbour Principles were the result.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] According to critics the Safe Harbour Principles do not provide for an adequate level of protection, because they contain fewer obligations for the controller and allow the contractual waiver of certain rights.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] In October 2015 the European Court of Justice ruled that the Safe Harbour regime was invalid as a result of an action brought by an Austrian privacy campaigner in relation to the export of subscribers' data by Facebook's European business to Facebook in the United States.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The US and European Authorities worked on a replacement for Safe Harbour and an agreement was reached in February 2016, leading to the European Commission adopting the EU–US Privacy Shield framework on 12 July 2016.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] This was likewise found invalid in 2020 and replaced with the EU–US Data Privacy Framework in 2023.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] In July 2007, a new, controversial, passenger name record (PNR) agreement between the US and the EU was undersigned.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] In February 2008, Jonathan Faull, the head of the EU's Commission of Home Affairs, complained about the United States bilateral policy concerning PNR.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The US had signed in February 2008 a memorandum of understanding (MOU) with the Czech Republic in exchange of a visa waiver scheme, without first consulting Brussels.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The tensions between Washington and Brussels are mainly caused by the lower level of data protection in the US, especially since foreigners do not benefit from the US Privacy Act of 1974.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] Other countries approached for bilateral Memoranda of Understanding included the United Kingdom, Estonia, (Germany) and Greece.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] EU directives are addressed to the member states, and are not legally binding for individuals in principle.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The member states must transpose the directive into internal law.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] Directive 95/46/EC on the protection of personal data had to be transposed by the end of 1998.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] All member states had enacted their own data protection legislation.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The original proposal also dictated that the legislation would in theory "apply for all non-EU companies without any establishment in the EU, provided that the processing of data is directed at EU residents," one of the biggest changes with the new legislation.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] This change carried on through to the legislation's final approval on 14 April 2016, affecting entities around the world.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] "The Regulation applies to processing outside the EU that relates to the offering of goods or services to data subjects (individuals) in the EU or the monitoring of their behavior," according to W.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The EC then set a compliance date of 25 May 2018, giving businesses around the world a chance to prepare for compliance, review data protection language in contracts, consider transition to international standards, update privacy policies, and review marketing plans.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] As of 2003, the United States has no single data protection law comparable to the EU's Data Protection Directive.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] Therefore, while certain sectors may already satisfy parts of the EU Directive most do not.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The United States prefers what it calls a 'sectoral' approach to data protection legislation, which relies on a combination of legislation, regulation, and self-regulation, rather than governmental regulation alone.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] Former US President Bill Clinton and former Vice-President Al Gore explicitly recommended in their "Framework for Global Electronic Commerce" that the private sector should lead, and companies should implement self-regulation in reaction to issues brought on by Internet technology.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The reasoning behind this approach has as much to do with American laissez-faire economics as with different social perspectives.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] The First Amendment of the United States Constitution guarantees the right to free speech.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] While free speech is an explicit right guaranteed by the United States Constitution, privacy is an implicit right guaranteed by the Constitution as interpreted by the United States Supreme Court, although it is often an explicit right in many state constitutions.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] Europe's extensive privacy regulation is justified with reference to experiences under World War II-era fascist governments and post-War Communist regimes, where there was widespread unchecked use of personal information.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] World War II and the post-War period was a time in Europe when disclosure of race or ethnicity led to secret denunciations and seizures that sent friends and neighbours to work camps and concentration camps.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] In the age of computers, Europeans' guardedness of secret government files has translated into a distrust of corporate databases, and governments in Europe took decided steps to protect personal information from abuses in the years following World War II.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] (Germany) and France, in particular, set forth comprehensive data protection laws.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] Critics of Europe's data policies, however, have said that they have impeded Europe's ability to monetize the data of users on the internet and are the primary reason why there are no Big Tech companies in Europe, with most of them instead being in the United States.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] Furthermore, with Alibaba and Tencent joining the ranks of the world's 10 most valuable tech companies in recent years, even China is moving ahead of Europe in the performance of its digital economy, which was valued at $5.09 trillion in 2019 (35.8 trillion yuan).
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] In addition to governmental and institutional measures, independent research and educational platforms have emerged to promote stronger data-protection awareness and responsible digital practices across regions.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] More recently, jurisdictions outside Europe and the United States have begun adopting hybrid data-protection models that blend the rights-based approach of the GDPR with the sectoral and regulatory flexibility of American law.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] For example, Nigeria’s Nigeria Data Protection Act (NDPA) develops a unified legislative framework inspired by the GDPR but tailored to the market realities of emerging economies.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] A detailed comparative analysis on Privacy Needle(2025) explores key differences such as territorial scope, consent and lawful-basis models, cross-border data-flow regulation, and enforcement regimes.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] Sites such as Privacy Needle publish comparative analyses of global privacy frameworks—including the EU’s GDPR, Nigeria’s NDPA, and U.S. sectoral laws—helping policymakers, professionals, and the public understand evolving data-governance trends.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-directive] These initiatives contribute to informed discussions on the balance between innovation, privacy rights, and cybersecurity in the modern digital economy.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-officer] A **data protection officer** (**DPO**) ensures within an organization that the laws protecting individuals' personal data are implemented.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-officer] The designation, position and tasks of a DPO within an organization are described in Articles 37, 38 and 39 of the European Union (EU) General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-officer] Many other countries require the appointment of a DPO, and it is becoming more prevalent in privacy legislation.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-officer] The ability of a DPO to operate independently is considered to be "of utmost importance".
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-officer] According to the GDPR, the DPO should report directly to the highest management level.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-officer] This does not mean that the DPO has to be directly managed at this level, but they must have direct access to give advice to senior managers who are making decisions about personal data processing.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-officer] The core responsibilities of the DPO include ensuring that his/her organization is aware of, and trained on, all relevant GDPR obligations.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-officer] Common tasks of a DPO include ensuring proper processes are in place for subject access requests, data mapping, privacy impact assessments, as well as raising data privacy awareness with employees.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-officer] Additionally, they must conduct audits to ensure compliance, address potential issues proactively, and act as a liaison between his/her organization and the public regarding all data privacy matters.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-officer] In Germany, a 2001 law established a requirement for a DPO in certain organizations and included various protections around the scope and tenure for the role, including protections against dismissal for bringing problems to the attention of management.
[src:gdpr-compliance/data-protection-officer] Many of these concepts were incorporated into the drafting of Article 38 of the GDPR and have continued to be incorporated in other privacy standards.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The **General Data Protection Regulation** (Regulation (EU) 2016/679), abbreviated **GDPR**, is a European Union regulation on information privacy in the European Union (EU) and the European Economic Area (EEA).
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR is an important component of EU privacy law and human rights law, in particular Article 8(1) of the Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It also governs the transfer of personal data outside the EU and EEA.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR's goals are to enhance individuals' control and rights over their personal information and to simplify the regulations for international business.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It supersedes the Data Protection Directive 95/46/EC and, among other things, simplifies the terminology.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The European Parliament and Council of the European Union adopted the GDPR on 14 April 2016, to become effective on 25 May 2018.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] As an EU regulation (instead of a directive), the GDPR has direct legal effect and does not require transposition into national law.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] However, it also provides flexibility for individual member states to modify (derogate from) some of its provisions.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] As an example of the Brussels effect, the regulation became a model for many other laws around the world, including in Brazil, Japan, Singapore, South Africa, South Korea, Sri Lanka, and Thailand.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] After leaving the European Union, the United Kingdom enacted its "UK GDPR", identical to the GDPR.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA), adopted on 28 June 2018, has many similarities with the GDPR.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR also contains 173 recitals purposed to clarify scope and rationale for the regulatory provisions, as well as its legislative intents – Recital 4, for instance, begins by saying that the processing of personal data should be "designed to serve mankind".
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The regulation applies if the data controller, or processor, or the data subject (person) is based in the EU.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The regulation also applies to organisations based outside the EU if they collect or process personal data of individuals located inside the EU.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The regulation does not apply to the processing of data by private persons provided that the purpose has no connection to a professional or commercial activity." (Recital 18).
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] According to the European Commission, "Personal data is information that relates to an identified or identifiable individual.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] If you cannot directly identify an individual from that information, then you need to consider whether the individual is still identifiable.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The data protection reform package also includes a separate Data Protection Directive for the police and criminal justice sector that provides rules on personal data exchanges at State level, Union level, and international levels.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A single set of rules applies to all EU member states.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Each member state establishes an independent supervisory authority (SA) to hear and investigate complaints, sanction administrative offences, etc.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] SAs in each member state co-operate with other SAs, providing mutual assistance and organising joint operations.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] If a business has multiple establishments in the EU, it must have a single SA as its "lead authority", based on the location of its "main establishment" where the main processing activities take place.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The lead authority thus acts as a "one-stop shop" to supervise all the processing activities of that business throughout the EU.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A European Data Protection Board (EDPB) co-ordinates the SAs.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] EDPB thus replaces the **Article 29** Data Protection Working Party.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] There are exceptions for data processed in an employment context or in national security that still might be subject to individual country regulations.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] If informed *consent* is used as the lawful basis for processing, consent must have been explicit for data collected and each purpose data is used for.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Consent must be a specific, freely given, plainly worded, and unambiguous affirmation given by the data subject; an online form which has consent options structured as an opt-out selected by default is a violation of the GDPR, as the consent is not unambiguously affirmed by the user.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In addition, multiple types of processing may not be "bundled" together into a single affirmation prompt, as this is not specific to each use of data, and the individual permissions are not freely given.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data subjects must be allowed to withdraw this consent at any time, and the process of doing so must not be harder than it was to opt in.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A data controller may not refuse service to users who decline consent to processing that is not strictly necessary in order to use the service.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Consent for children, defined in the regulation as being less than 16 years old (although with the option for member states to individually make it as low as 13 years old), must be given by the child's parent or custodian, and verifiable.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] If consent to processing was already provided under the Data Protection Directive, a data controller does not have to re-obtain consent if the processing is documented and obtained in compliance with the GDPR's requirements (Recital 171).
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The right of access (**Article 15**) is a data subject right.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It gives people the right to access their personal data and information about how this personal data is being processed.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A data subject must be able to transfer personal data from one electronic processing system to and into another, without being prevented from doing so by the data controller.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data that has been sufficiently anonymised is excluded, but data that has been only de-identified but remains possible to link to the individual in question, such as by providing the relevant identifier, is not.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Both data being 'provided' by the data subject and data being 'observed', such as about behaviour, are included.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In addition, the data must be provided by the controller in a structured and commonly used standard electronic format.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The right to data portability is provided by **Article 20**.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A *right to be forgotten* was replaced by a more limited *right of erasure* in the version of the GDPR that was adopted by the European Parliament in March 2014.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] There are some instances where this objection does not apply.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A task being carried out for public interest.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] GDPR is also clear that the data controller must inform individuals of their right to object from the first communication the controller has with them.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] This should be clear and separate from any other information the controller is providing and give them their options for how best to object to the processing of their data.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] There are instances the controller can refuse a request, in the circumstances that the objection request is "manifestly unfounded" or "excessive", so each case of objection must be looked at individually.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Other countries such as Canada are also, following the GDPR, considering legislation to regulate automated decision making under privacy laws, even though there are policy questions as to whether this is the best way to regulate AI.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In the judgment *Österreichische Post* (C-300/21) the Court of Justice of the European Union gave an interpretation of the right to compensation.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Article 82(1) GDPR requires for the award of damages *(i)* an infringement of the GDPR, *(ii)* (actual) damage suffered and *(iii)* a causal link between the infringement and the damage suffered.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It is not necessary that the damage suffered reaches a certain degree of seriousness.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] There is no European defined concept of damage.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Compensation is determined nationally in accordance with national law.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data processors are only liable for damage caused by processing in breach of obligations specifically imposed on processors by the GDPR, or for damage caused by processing which is outside, or contrary to, the lawful instructions of the data controller.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data controllers must clearly disclose any data collection, declare the lawful basis and purpose for data processing, and state how long data is being retained and if it is being shared with any third parties or outside of the EEA.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Firms have the obligation to protect data of employees and consumers to the degree where only the necessary data is extracted with minimum interference with data privacy from employees, consumers, or third parties.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Firms should have internal controls and regulations for various departments such as audit, internal controls, and operations.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data subjects have the right to request a portable copy of the data collected by a controller in a common format, as well as the right to have their data erased under certain circumstances.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Public authorities, and businesses whose core activities consist of regular or systematic processing of personal data, are required to employ a *data protection officer* (DPO), who is responsible for managing compliance with the GDPR.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data controllers must report data breaches to national supervisory authorities within 72 hours if they have an adverse effect on user privacy.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In some cases, violators of the GDPR may be fined up to €20 million or up to 4% of the annual worldwide turnover of the preceding financial year in case of an enterprise, whichever is greater.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] To be able to demonstrate compliance with the GDPR, the data controller must implement measures that meet the principles of data protection by design and by default.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] **Article 25** requires data protection measures to be designed into the development of business processes for products and services.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Such measures include pseudonymising personal data, by the controller, as soon as possible (Recital 78).
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It is the responsibility and the liability of the data controller to implement effective measures and be able to demonstrate the compliance of processing activities even if the processing is carried out by a data processor on behalf of the controller (Recital 74).
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] As such, the data subject must also be provided with contact details for the data controller and their designated data protection officer, where applicable.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data protection impact assessments (**Article 35**) have to be conducted when specific risks occur to the rights and freedoms of data subjects.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Risk assessment and mitigation is required and prior approval of the data protection authorities is required for high risks.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A report by the European Union Agency for Network and Information Security elaborates on what needs to be done to achieve privacy and data protection by default.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It specifies that encryption and decryption operations must be carried out locally, not by remote service, because both keys and data must remain in the power of the data owner if any privacy is to be achieved.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The report specifies that outsourced data storage on remote clouds is practical and relatively safe if only the data owner, not the cloud service, holds the decryption keys.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] An example is encryption, which renders the original data unintelligible in a process that cannot be reversed without access to the correct decryption key.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR requires for the additional information (such as the decryption key) to be kept separately from the pseudonymised data.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Another example of pseudonymisation is tokenisation, which is a non-mathematical approach to protecting data at rest that replaces sensitive data with non-sensitive substitutes, referred to as tokens.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] While the tokens have no extrinsic or exploitable meaning or value, they allow for specific data to be fully or partially visible for processing and analytics while sensitive information is kept hidden.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Tokenisation does not alter the type or length of data, which means it can be processed by legacy systems such as databases that may be sensitive to data length and type.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] This also requires much fewer computational resources to process and less storage space in databases than traditionally encrypted data.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Pseudonymisation is a privacy-enhancing technology and is recommended to reduce the risks to the concerned data subjects and also to help controllers and processors to meet their data protection obligations (Recital 28).
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Such requirements may be modified by each EU country.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The records shall be in electronic form and the controller or the processor and, where applicable, the controller's or the processor's representative, shall make the record available to the supervisory authority on request.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Controllers and processors of personal data must put in place *appropriate technical and organizational measures* to implement the data protection principles.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Business processes that handle personal data must be designed and built with consideration of the principles and provide safeguards to protect data (for example, using pseudonymization or full anonymization where appropriate).
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Data controllers must design information systems with privacy in mind.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] For instance, using the highest-possible privacy settings by default, so that the datasets are not publicly available by default and cannot be used to identify a subject.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] No personal data may be processed unless this processing is done under one of the six lawful bases specified by the regulation (consent, contract, public task, vital interest, legitimate interest or legal requirement).
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] When the processing is based on consent the data subject has the right to revoke it at any time.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A designated DPO can be a current member of staff of a controller or processor, or the role can be outsourced to an external person or agency through a service contract.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In any case, the processing body must make sure that there is no conflict of interest in other roles or interests that a DPO may hold.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The contact details for the DPO must be published by the processing organisation (for example, in a privacy notice) and registered with the supervisory authority.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The DPO is similar to a compliance officer and is also expected to be proficient at managing IT processes, data security (including dealing with cyberattacks) and other critical business continuity issues associated with the holding and processing of personal and sensitive data.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The skill set required stretches beyond understanding legal compliance with data protection laws and regulations.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The DPO must maintain a living data inventory of all data collected and stored on behalf of the organization.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] More details on the function and the role of data protection officer were given on 13 December 2016 (revised 5 April 2017) in a guideline document.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Organisations based outside the EU must also appoint an EU-based person as a representative and point of contact for their GDPR obligations.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] This is a distinct role from a DPO, although there is overlap in responsibilities that suggest that this role can also be held by the designated DPO.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Article 42 and 43 of the GDPR set the legal basis for formal GDPR certifications.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] 42 GDPR, the purpose of this certification is to demonstrate “compliance with the GDPR of processing operations by controllers and processors”.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR certification also contributes to reduce the legal and financial risks of applicants, as well as of data controllers using certified data processing services.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The adoption of the European Data Protection Seals is under the responsibility of the European Data Protection Board (EDPB) and is recognized across all EU and EEA Member States.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In October 2022, the Europrivacy certification criteria were officially recognized by the European Data Protection Board (EDPB) to serve as European Data Protection Seal.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Europrivacy was developed by the European research programme and is managed by the European Centre for Certification and Privacy (ECCP) in Luxembourg.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] These are some cases which are not addressed in the GDPR specifically, thus are treated as exemptions.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Conversely, an entity or more precisely an "enterprise" has to be engaged in "economic activity" to be covered by the GDPR.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Economic activity is defined broadly under European Union competition law.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The regulation applies regardless of where the processing takes place.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] This has been interpreted as intentionally giving GDPR extraterritorial jurisdiction for non-EU establishments if they are doing business with people located in the EU.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It is questionable whether the EU or its member states will in practice be able to enforce GDPR against organisations which have no establishment in the EU.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Under **Article 27**, non-EU establishments subject to GDPR are obliged to have a designee within the European Union, an "EU Representative", to serve as a point of contact for their obligations under the regulation.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The EU Representative is the Controller's or Processor's contact person vis-à-vis European privacy supervisors and data subjects, in all matters relating to processing, to ensure compliance with this GDPR.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A natural (individual) or legal (corporation) person can play the role of an EU Representative.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The non-EU establishment must issue a duly signed document (letter of accreditation) designating a given individual or company as its EU Representative.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The said designation can only be given in writing.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The intentional or negligent (willful blindness) character of the infringement (failure to designate an EU Representative) may rather constitute aggravating factors.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Non-EU public authorities and bodies are equally exempted.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Binding corporate rules, standard contractual clauses for data protection issued by a Data Processing Agreement (DPA), or a scheme of binding and enforceable commitments by the data controller or processor situated in a third country, are among examples.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The applicability of GDPR in the United Kingdom is affected by Brexit.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Although the United Kingdom formally withdrew from the European Union on 31 January 2020, it remained subject to EU law, including GDPR, until the end of the transition period on 31 December 2020.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Under the European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018, existing and relevant EU law was transposed into UK law upon completion of the transition, and the GDPR was amended by statutory instrument to remove certain provisions no longer needed due to the UK's non-membership in the EU.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Thereafter, the regulation is referred to as "UK GDPR".
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The UK does not restrict the transfer of personal data to countries within the EEA under UK GDPR.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] As part of the withdrawal agreement, the European Commission committed to perform an adequacy assessment.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] On 28 June 2021, the Commission confirmed the adequacy of the UK GDPR for four years; This was set to expire on 27 June 2025, but was extended for six months to give the Commission time to assess the impact of the Data (Use and Access) Act 2025.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] On 19 December 2025 the Commission renewed the 2021 adequacy decision until 27 December 2031.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] In March 2021, Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Oliver Dowden stated that the UK was exploring divergence from the EU GDPR in order to "[focus] more on the outcomes that we want to have and less on the burdens of the rules imposed on individual businesses".
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] As per a study conducted by Deloitte in 2018, 92% of companies believe they are able to comply with GDPR in their business practices in the long run.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Companies operating outside of the EU have invested heavily to align their business practices with GDPR.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The area of GDPR consent has a number of implications for businesses who record calls as a matter of practice.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A typical disclaimer is not considered sufficient to gain assumed consent to record calls.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Additionally, when recording has commenced, should the caller withdraw their consent, then the agent receiving the call must be able to stop a previously started recording and ensure the recording does not get stored.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] IT professionals expect that compliance with the GDPR will require additional investment overall: over 80 percent of those surveyed expected GDPR-related spending to be at least US$100,000.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] It has been argued that smaller businesses and startup companies might not have the financial resources to adequately comply with the GDPR, unlike the larger international technology firms (such as Facebook and Google) that the regulation is ostensibly meant to target first and foremost.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A lack of knowledge and understanding of the regulations has also been a concern in the lead-up to its adoption.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] A counter-argument to this has been that companies were made aware of these changes two years prior to them coming into effect and should have had enough time to prepare.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The regulations, including whether an enterprise must have a data protection officer, have been criticized for potential administrative burden and unclear compliance requirements.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] There is also concern regarding the implementation of the GDPR in blockchain systems, as the transparent and fixed record of blockchain transactions contradicts the very nature of the GDPR.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Many media outlets have commented on the introduction of a "right to explanation" of algorithmic decisions, but legal scholars have since argued that the existence of such a right is highly unclear without judicial tests and is limited at best.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] The GDPR has garnered support from businesses who regard it as an opportunity to improve their data management.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Mark Zuckerberg has also called it a "very positive step for the Internet", and has called for GDPR-style laws to be adopted in the US.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Consumer rights groups such as The European Consumer Organisation are among the most vocal proponents of the legislation.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Other supporters have attributed its passage to the whistleblower Edward Snowden.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p01] Free software advocate Richard Stallman has praised some aspects of the GDPR but called for additional safeguards to prevent technology companies from "manufacturing consent".
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Academic experts who participated in the formulation of the GDPR wrote that the law "is the most consequential regulatory development in information policy in a generation.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Despite having had at least two years to prepare and do so, many companies and websites changed their privacy policies and features worldwide directly prior to GDPR's implementation, and customarily provided email and other notifications discussing these changes.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Phishing scams also emerged using falsified versions of GDPR-related emails, and it was also argued that some GDPR notice emails may have actually been sent in violation of anti-spam laws.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In March 2019, a provider of compliance software found that many websites operated by EU member state governments contained embedded tracking from ad technology providers.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] A blog, *GDPR Hall of Shame*, was also created to showcase unusual delivery of GDPR notices, and attempts at compliance that contained egregious violations of the regulation's requirements.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Its author remarked that the regulation "has a lot of nitty gritty, in-the-weeds details, but not a lot of information about how to comply", but also acknowledged that businesses had two years to comply, making some of its responses unjustified.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Research indicates that approximately 25% of software vulnerabilities have GDPR implications.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Since Article 33 emphasizes breaches, not bugs, security experts advise companies to invest in processes and capabilities to identify vulnerabilities before they can be exploited, including coordinated vulnerability disclosure processes.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] An investigation of Android apps' privacy policies, data access capabilities, and data access behaviour has shown that numerous apps display a somewhat privacy-friendlier behaviour since the GDPR was implemented, although they still retain most of their data access privileges in their code.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] An investigation of the Norwegian Consumer Council into the post-GDPR data subject dashboards on social media platforms (such as Google dashboard) has concluded that large social media firms deploy deceptive tactics in order to discourage their customers from sharpening their privacy settings.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Some companies, such as Klout, and several online video games, ceased operations entirely to coincide with its implementation, citing the GDPR as a burden on their continued operations, especially due to the business model of the former.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The volume of online behavioural advertising placements in Europe fell 25–40% on 25 May 2018.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Facebook and subsidiaries WhatsApp and Instagram, as well as Google LLC (targeting Android), were immediately sued by Max Schrems's non-profit NOYB just hours after midnight on 25 May 2018, for their use of "forced consent".
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Schrems asserts that both companies violated Article 7(4) by not presenting opt-ins for data processing consent on an individualized basis, and requiring users to consent to all data processing activities (including those not strictly necessary) or would be forbidden from using the services.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] On 21 January 2019, Google was fined €50 million by the French DPA for showing insufficient control, consent, and transparency over use of personal data for behavioural advertising.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In November 2018, following a journalistic investigation into Liviu Dragnea, the Romanian DPA (ANSPDCP) used a GDPR request to demand information on the RISE Project's sources.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In July 2019, the British Information Commissioner's Office issued an intention to fine British Airways a record £183 million (1.5% of turnover) for poor security arrangements that enabled a 2018 web skimming attack affecting around 380,000 transactions.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] British Airways was ultimately fined a reduced amount of £20m, with the ICO noting that they had "considered both representations from BA and the economic impact of COVID-19 on their business before setting a final penalty".
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Critics interviewed by *Politico* also argued that enforcement was also being hampered by varying interpretations between member states, the prioritisation of guidance over enforcement by some authorities, and a lack of cooperation between member states.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In November 2021, Irish Council for Civil Liberties lodged a formal complaint of the Commission that it is in breach of its obligation under EU Law to carefully monitor how Ireland applies the GDPR.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Until January 2023, the Commission published a new commitment based on the complaint of ICCL.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] While companies are now subject to legal obligations, there are still various inconsistencies in the practical and technical implementation of GDPR.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] As an example, according to the GDPR's right to access, the companies are obliged to provide data subjects with the data they gather about them.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] However, in a study on loyalty cards in Germany, companies did not provide the data subjects with the exact information of the purchased articles.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] One might argue that such companies do not collect the information of the purchased articles, which does not conform with their business models.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Therefore, data subjects tend to see that as a GDPR violation.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] As a result, studies have suggested for a better control through authorities.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] According to the GDPR, end-users' consent should be valid, freely given, specific, informed and active.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] However, the lack of enforceability regarding obtaining lawful consents has been a challenge.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] As an example, a 2020 study, showed that the Big Tech, i.e.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Google, Amazon, Facebook, Apple, and Microsoft (GAFAM), use dark patterns in their consent obtaining mechanisms, which raises doubts regarding the lawfulness of the acquired consent.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In March 2021, EU member states led by France were reported to be attempting to modify the impact of the privacy regulation in Europe by exempting national security agencies.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] After around 160 million Euros in GDPR fines were imposed in 2020, the figure was already over one billion Euros in 2021.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In 2024 and early 2025, GDPR enforcement actions intensified.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The Irish Data Protection Commission (DPC) imposed a €345 million fine on TikTok for violations related to children's data privacy and insufficient safeguards for young users.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In January 2025, Meta was fined €1.2 billion for unlawful data transfers between the EU and the US, marking one of the largest GDPR fines to date.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] On 12 February 2025, the European Commission abandoned proposed regulations on technology patents, AI liability, and privacy for messaging apps due to strong lobbying and a lack of consensus among EU lawmakers, with major tech firms opposing the changes.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Mass adoption of these new privacy standards by multinational companies has been cited as an example of the "Brussels effect", a phenomenon wherein European laws and regulations are used as a baseline due to their gravitas.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The U.S. state of California passed the California Consumer Privacy Act on 28 June 2018, taking effect on 1 January 2020; it grants rights to transparency and control over the collection of personal information by companies in a similar means to GDPR.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Critics have argued that such laws need to be implemented at the federal level to be effective, as a collection of state-level laws would have varying standards that would complicate compliance.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Two other U.S. states have since enacted similar legislation: Virginia passed the Consumer Data Privacy Act on 2 March 2021, and Colorado enacted the Colorado Privacy Act on 8 July 2021.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The Republic of Turkey, a candidate for European Union membership, adopted the Law on The Protection of Personal Data on 24 March 2016 in compliance with the EU acquis.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] China's 2021 Personal Information Protection Law is the country's first comprehensive law on personal data rights and is modelled after the GDPR.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] Switzerland will also adopt a new data protection law that largely follows EU's GDPR.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The CLOUD Act, enacted in 2018, is seen by the European Data Protection Supervisor (EDPS) as a law in possible conflict with the GDPR.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] A 2024 study found that GDPR reduced both EU user website page views and website revenue by 12%.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The EU Digital Single Market strategy relates to "digital economy" activities related to businesses and people in the EU.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] As part of the strategy, the GDPR and the NIS Directive all apply from 25 May 2018.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The proposed ePrivacy Regulation was also planned to be applicable from 25 May 2018, but will be delayed for several months.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] The eIDAS Regulation is also part of the strategy.
[src:gdpr-compliance/general-data-protection-regulation-p02] In an initial assessment, the European Council has stated that the GDPR should be considered "a prerequisite for the development of future digital policy initiatives".
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The abbreviation PII is widely used in the United States, but the phrase it abbreviates has four common variants based on *personal* or *personally*, and *identifiable* or *identifying*.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Not all are equivalent, and for legal purposes the effective definitions vary depending on the jurisdiction and the purposes for which the term is being used.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Under European Union and United Kingdom data protection regimes, which centre primarily on the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), the term "personal data" is significantly broader, and determines the scope of the regulatory regime.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Personal data is defined under the GDPR as "any information which [is] related to an identified or identifiable natural person".
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The IP address of an Internet subscriber may be classed as personal data.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The concept of PII has become prevalent as information technology and the Internet have made it easier to collect PII leading to a profitable market in collecting and reselling PII.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] PII can also be exploited by criminals to stalk or steal the identity of a person, or to aid in the planning of criminal acts.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] As a response to these threats, many website privacy policies specifically address the gathering of PII, and lawmakers such as the European Parliament have enacted a series of legislative acts such as the GDPR to limit the distribution and accessibility of PII.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Serious confusion arises around whether PII means information which is identifiable (that is, can be associated with a person) or identifying (that is, associated uniquely with a person, such that the PII *identifies* them).
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] In prescriptive data privacy regimes such as the US federal Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA), PII items have been specifically defined.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] In broader data protection regimes such as the GDPR, personal data is defined in a non-prescriptive principles-based way.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Information that might not count as PII under HIPAA can be personal data for the purposes of GDPR.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] For this reason, "PII" is typically deprecated internationally.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] In the EU rules, there has been a more specific notion that the data subject can potentially be identified through additional processing of other attributes—quasi- or pseudo-identifiers.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] A simple example of this distinction: the color name "red" by itself is *not* personal data, but that same value stored as part of a person's record as their "favorite color" *is* personal data; it is the connection to the person that makes it personal data, not (as in PII) the value itself.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The concept of information combination given in the SB1386 definition is key to correctly distinguishing PII, as defined by OMB, from "personal information", as defined by SB1386.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Information, such as a name, that lacks context cannot be said to be SB1386 "personal information", but it must be said to be PII as defined by OMB.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] For example, the name "John Smith" has no meaning in the current context and is therefore not SB1386 "personal information", but it is PII.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] A Social Security Number (SSN) without a name or some other associated identity or context information is not SB1386 "personal information", but it is PII.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] For example, the SSN 078-05-1120 by itself is PII, but it is not SB1386 "personal information".
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] However the combination of a valid name with the correct SSN is SB1386 "personal information".
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The combination of a name with a context may also be considered PII; for example, if a person's name is on a list of patients for an HIV clinic.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] However, it is not necessary for the name to be combined with a context in order for it to be PII.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The reason for this distinction is that bits of information such as names, although they may not be sufficient by themselves to make an identification, may later be combined with other information to identify persons and expose them to harm.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The scope of the term "sensitive personal data" varies by jurisdiction.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] In the UK, personal health data is treated as "sensitive" and in need of additional data protection measures.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] According to the OMB, in the United States it is not always the case that PII is "sensitive", and context may be taken into account in deciding whether certain PII is or is not sensitive.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] When a person wishes to remain anonymous, descriptions of them will often employ several of the above, such as "a 34-year-old white male who works at Target".
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Information can still be *private*, in the sense that a person may not wish for it to become publicly known, without being personally identifiable.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Moreover, sometimes multiple pieces of information, none sufficient by itself to uniquely identify an individual, may uniquely identify a person when combined; this is one reason that multiple pieces of evidence are usually presented at criminal trials.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] It has been shown that, in 1990, 87% of the population of the United States could be uniquely identified by gender, ZIP code, and full date of birth.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] In hacker and Internet slang, the practice of finding and releasing such information is called "doxing".
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] It is sometimes used to deter collaboration with law enforcement.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] On occasion, the doxing can trigger an arrest, particularly if law enforcement agencies suspect that the "doxed" individual may panic and disappear.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] It appears that this definition is significantly broader than the Californian example given above, and thus that Australian privacy law may cover a broader category of data and information than in some US law.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The term "PII" is not used in Australian privacy law.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] European Union data protection law does not use the concept of personally identifiable information, and its scope is instead determined by the non-synonymous, wider concept of "personal data".
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Further examples can be found on the EU privacy website.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] On 1 June 2023, the Hong Kong Office of the Privacy Commissioner for Personal Data published an investigation report on a data breach involving the unauthorised access of a credit reference database platform.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The Report highlights the need for organizations to take adequate steps to protect personal data as the mere imposition of contractual obligations and policies is insufficient if such obligations and policies are not effective or are not enforced.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The Report also clarifies that credit data is a form of "sensitive" personal data.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The twelve Information Privacy Principles of the Privacy Act 1993 apply.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] New Zealand enacted the Privacy Act in 2020 to promote and protect individual privacy.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The Federal Act on Data Protection of 19 June 1992 (in force since 1993) has set up a protection of privacy by prohibiting virtually any processing of personal data which is not expressly authorized by the data subjects.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The protection is subject to the authority of the Federal Data Protection and Information Commissioner.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Additionally, any person may ask in writing a company managing data files to correct or delete any personal data.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The company must respond within thirty days.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] One of the primary focuses of the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) is to protect a patient's Protected Health Information (PHI), which is similar to PII.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Senate proposed the Privacy Act of 2005, which attempted to strictly limit the display, purchase, or sale of PII without the person's consent.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Similarly, the (proposed) Anti-Phishing Act of 2005 attempted to prevent the acquiring of PII through phishing.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] U.S. lawmakers have paid special attention to the social security number because it can be easily used to commit identity theft.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The (proposed) Social Security Number Protection Act of 2005 and (proposed) Identity Theft Prevention Act of 2005 each sought to limit the distribution of an individual's social security number.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Additional U.S.-specific personally identifiable information includes, but is not limited to, I-94 records, Medicaid ID numbers, and Internal Revenue Service (I.R.S.) documentation.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Exclusivity of personally identifiable information affiliated with the U.S. highlights national data security concerns and the influence of personally identifiable information in U.S. federal data management systems.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) is a physical sciences laboratory, and a non-regulatory agency of the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Its mission is to promote innovation and industrial competitiveness.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The following are less often used to distinguish individual identity, because they are traits shared by many people.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] However, they are potentially PII, because they may be combined with other personal information to identify an individual.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] In forensics, particularly the identification and prosecution of criminals, personally identifiable information is critical in establishing evidence in criminal procedure.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Personal data is a key component of online identity and can be exploited by individuals.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] For instance, data can be altered and used to create fake documents, hijack mail boxes and phone calls or harass people, as occurred in 2019 to a customer of the EE mobile phone operator in the UK.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Another category can be referred to as financial identity theft, which usually entails bank account and credit card information being stolen, and then being used or sold.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Personal data can also be used to create fake online identities, including fake accounts and profiles (which can be referred as identity cloning or identity fraud) for celebrities to gather data from other users more easily.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Even individuals can be concerned, especially for personal purposes (this is more widely known as sockpuppetry).
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The most critical information, such as one's password, date of birth, ID documents or social security number, can be used to log in to different websites (e.g. password reuse and account verification) to gather more information and access more content.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Also, several agencies ask for discretion on subjects related to their work, for the safety of their employees.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] For this reason, the United States Department of Defense (DoD) has strict policies controlling release of personally identifiable information of DoD personnel.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Many intelligence agencies have similar policies, sometimes to the point where employees do not disclose to their friends that they work for the agency.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Similar identity protection concerns exist for witness protection programs, women's shelters, and victims of domestic violence and other threats.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Personal information removal services work by identifying and requesting data brokers to delete the personal information of their clients.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] This process can be manual or fully automated, but it is nevertheless complex because it involves dealing with numerous data brokers, each with different policies and procedures for data removal.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Companies offering personal information removal also face some issues.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] They struggle to ensure comprehensive data removal as new data brokers emerge and existing ones don’t always comply with removal requests.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Most of them are also limited to certain regions or countries.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] During the second half of the 20th century, the digital revolution introduced "privacy economics", or the trade of personal data.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The value of data can change over time and over different contexts.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Disclosing data can reverse information asymmetry, though the costs of doing so can be unclear.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] In relation to companies, consumers often have "imperfect information regarding when their data is collected, with what purposes, and with what consequences".
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] In the mid-1990s, Varian retook the Chicago Boys approach and added a new externality, stating that the consumer would not always have perfect information on how their own data would be used.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Laudon developed a model in which individuals own their data and have the ability to sell it as a product.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] He believed that such a system should not be regulated, to create a free market.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] In the 2000s, researchers worked on price discrimination (Taylor, 2004), two-sided markets (Cornière, 2011) and marketing strategies (Anderson and de Palma, 2012).
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The theories became complex, and showed that the impact of privacy on the economy highly depended on the context.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Sources, usually Internet-based since the 1990s, may include census and electoral roll records, social networking sites, court reports and purchase histories.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] The information from data brokers may be used in background checks used by employers and housing.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] There are varying regulations around the world limiting the collection of information on individuals; privacy laws vary.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] In the United States there is no federal regulation protection for the consumer from data brokers, although some states have begun enacting laws individually.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] In the European Union, GDPR serves to regulate data brokers' operations.
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Some data brokers report to have large numbers of population data or "data attributes".
[src:gdpr-compliance/personal-data] Acxiom purports to have data from 2.5 billion different people.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Recent developments in computer science and data engineering, such as support for encoding privacy in data and the availability and quality of Privacy-Enhancing Technologies (PET's) partly offset those critiques and help to make the principles feasible in real-world settings.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The European GDPR regulation incorporates privacy by design.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The privacy by design framework was developed by Ann Cavoukian, Information and Privacy Commissioner of Ontario, following her joint work with the Dutch Data Protection Authority and the Netherlands Organisation for Applied Scientific Research in 1995.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] In 2009, the Information and Privacy Commissioner of Ontario co-hosted an event, *Privacy by Design: The Definitive Workshop*, with the Israeli Law, Information and Technology Authority at the 31st International Conference of Data Protection and Privacy Commissioners (2009).
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] In 2010 the framework achieved international acceptance when the International Assembly of Privacy Commissioners and Data Protection Authorities unanimously passed a resolution on privacy by design recognising it as an international standard at their annual conference.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Among other commitments, the commissioners resolved to promote privacy by design as widely as possible and foster the incorporation of the principle into policy and legislation.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The principles have been cited in over five hundred articles referring to the *Privacy by Design in Law, Policy and Practice* white paper by Ann Cavoukian.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The privacy by design approach is characterized by proactive rather than reactive measures.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] It anticipates and prevents privacy invasive events before they happen.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design does not wait for privacy risks to materialize, nor does it offer remedies for resolving privacy infractions once they have occurred — it aims to prevent them from occurring.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] In short, privacy by design comes before-the-fact, not after.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design seeks to deliver the maximum degree of privacy by ensuring that personal data are automatically protected in any given IT system or business practice.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] If an individual does nothing, their privacy still remains intact.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] No action is required on the part of the individual to protect their privacy — it is built into the system, by default.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design is embedded into the design and architecture of IT systems as well as business practices.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] It is not bolted on as an add-on, after the fact.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The result is that privacy becomes an essential component of the core functionality being delivered.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Privacy is integral to the system without diminishing functionality.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design seeks to accommodate all legitimate interests and objectives in a positive-sum “win-win” manner, not through a dated, zero-sum approach, where unnecessary trade-offs are made.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design avoids the pretense of false dichotomies, such as privacy versus security, demonstrating that it is possible to have both.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design, having been embedded into the system prior to the first element of information being collected, extends securely throughout the entire lifecycle of the data involved — strong security measures are essential to privacy, from start to finish.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] This ensures that all data are securely retained, and then securely destroyed at the end of the process, in a timely fashion.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Thus, privacy by design ensures cradle-to-grave, secure lifecycle management of information, end-to-end.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design seeks to assure all stakeholders that whatever business practice or technology involved is in fact operating according to the stated promises and objectives, subject to independent verification.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The component parts and operations remain visible and transparent, to users and providers alike.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Above all, privacy by design requires architects and operators to keep the interests of the individual uppermost by offering such measures as strong privacy defaults, appropriate notice, and empowering user-friendly options.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) approved the Committee on Consumer Policy (COPOLCO) proposal for a new ISO standard: *Consumer Protection: Privacy by Design for Consumer Goods and Services* (ISO/PC317).
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The standard will aim to specify the design process to provide consumer goods and services that meet consumers’ domestic processing privacy needs as well as the personal privacy requirements of data protection.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The standard has the UK as secretariat with thirteen participating members and twenty observing members.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The Standards Council of Canada (SCC) is one of the participating members and has established a mirror Canadian committee to ISO/PC317.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The OASIS Privacy by Design Documentation for Software Engineers (PbD-SE) Technical Committee provides a specification to operationalize privacy by design in the context of software engineering.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design, like security by design, is a normal part of the software development process and a risk reduction strategy for software engineers.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The PbD-SE specification translates the PbD principles to conformance requirements within software engineering tasks and helps software development teams to produce artifacts as evidence of PbD principle adherence.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design originated from privacy-enhancing technologies (PETs) in a joint 1995 report by Ann Cavoukian and John Borking.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] In 2007 the European Commission provided a memo on PETs.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] In 2008 the British Information Commissioner's Office commissioned a report titled *Privacy by Design – An Overview of Privacy Enhancing Technologies*.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] There are many facets to privacy by design.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] There is the technical side like software and systems engineering, administrative elements (e.g. legal, policy, procedural), other organizational controls, and operating contexts.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design evolved from early efforts to express fair information practice principles directly into the design and operation of information and communications technologies.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] In his publication *Privacy by Design: Delivering the Promises* Peter Hustinx acknowledges the key role played by Ann Cavoukian and John Borking, then Deputy Privacy Commissioners, in the joint 1995 publication *Privacy-Enhancing Technologies: The Path to Anonymity*.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] This 1995 report focussed on exploring technologies that permit transactions to be conducted anonymously.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Privacy-enhancing technologies allow online users to protect the privacy of their Personally Identifiable Information (PII) provided to and handled by services or applications.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design evolved to consider the broader systems and processes in which PETs were embedded and operated.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Center for Democracy & Technology (CDT) in *The Role of Privacy by Design in Protecting Consumer Privacy* distinguishes PET from privacy by design noting that “PETs are most useful for users who already understand online privacy risks.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] 4 *Teledienstedatenschutzgesetz* [Teleservices Data Protection Act]) in July 1997.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The new EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) includes ‘data protection by design’ and ‘data protection by default’, the second foundational principle of privacy by design.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Canada's Privacy Commissioner included privacy by design in its report on *Privacy, Trust and Innovation – Building Canada's Digital Advantage*.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] In Australia, the Commissioner for Privacy and Data Protection for the State of Victoria (CPDP) has formally adopted privacy by design as a core policy to underpin information privacy management in the Victorian public sector.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The UK Information Commissioner's Office website highlights privacy by design and data protection by design and default.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] In October 2014, the Mauritius Declaration on the Internet of Things was made at the 36th International Conference of Data Protection and Privacy Commissioners and included privacy by design and default.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The Privacy Commissioner for Personal Data, Hong Kong held an educational conference on the importance of privacy by design.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] In the private sector, Sidewalk Toronto commits to privacy by design principles; Brendon Lynch, Chief Privacy Officer at Microsoft, wrote an article called *Privacy by Design at Microsoft*; whilst Deloitte relates certifiably trustworthy to privacy by design.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The privacy by design framework attracted academic debate, particularly following the 2010 International Data Commissioners resolution that provided criticism of privacy by design with suggestions by legal and engineering experts to better understand how to apply the framework into various contexts.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Privacy by design has been critiqued as "vague" and leaving "many open questions about their application when engineering systems." Suggestions have been made to instead start with and focus on minimizing data, which can be done through security engineering.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Leuven published Engineering Privacy by Design noting that “The design and implementation of privacy requirements in systems is a difficult problem and requires translation of complex social, legal and ethical concerns into systems requirements”.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The principles of privacy by design "remain vague and leave many open questions about their application when engineering systems".
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The authors argue that "starting from data minimization is a necessary and foundational first step to engineer systems in line with the principles of privacy by design".
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] This is partly a more structural problem due to the fact that legal principles are abstract, open-ended with different possible interpretations and exceptions, whereas engineering practices require unambiguous meanings and formal definitions of design concepts.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] In 2011, the Danish National It and Telecom Agency published a discussion paper in which they argued that privacy by design is a key goal for creating digital security models, by extending the concept to "Security by Design".
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The objective is to balance anonymity and surveillance by eliminating identification as much as possible.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Another criticism is that current definitions of privacy by design do not address the methodological aspect of systems engineering, such as using decent system engineering methods, e.g. those which cover the complete system and data life cycle.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] This problem is further exacerbated in the move to networked digital infrastructures initiatives such as the smart city or the Internet of Things.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Whereas privacy by design has mainly been focused on the responsibilities of singular organisations for a certain technology, these initiatives often require the interoperability of many different technologies operated by different organisations.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] This requires a shift from organisational to infrastructural design.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The concept of privacy by design also does not focus on the role of the actual data holder but on that of the system designer.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] This role is not known in privacy law, so the concept of privacy by design is not based on law.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] This, in turn, undermines the trust by data subjects, data holders and policy-makers.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Questions have been raised from science and technology studies of whether privacy by design will change the meaning and practice of rights through implementation in technologies, organizations, standards and infrastructures.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] From a civil society perspective, some have even raised the possibility that a bad use of these design-based approaches can even lead to the danger of bluewashing.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] This refers to the minimal instrumental use by organizations of privacy design without adequate checks, in order to portray themselves as more privacy-friendly than is factually justified.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] It has also been pointed out that privacy by design is similar to voluntary compliance schemes in industries impacting the environment, and thus lacks the teeth necessary to be effective, and may differ per company.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] In addition, the evolutionary approach currently taken to the development of the concept will come at the cost of privacy infringements because evolution implies also letting unfit phenotypes (privacy-invading products) live until they are proven unfit.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Some critics have pointed out that certain business models are built around customer surveillance and data manipulation and therefore voluntary compliance is unlikely.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] In 2013, Rubinstein and Good used Google and Facebook privacy incidents to conduct a counterfactual analysis in order to identify lessons learned of value for regulators when recommending privacy by design.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The first was that “more detailed principles and specific examples” would be more helpful to companies.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The second is that “usability is just as important as engineering principles and practices”.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The third is that there needs to be more work on “refining and elaborating on design principles–both in privacy engineering and usability design”. including efforts to define international privacy standards.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The final lesson learned is that "regulators must do more than merely recommend the adoption and implementation of privacy by design".
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Rubinstein and Good also highlighted that privacy by design could result in applications that exemplified Privacy by Design and their work was well received.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The following sections of this opinion provide an overview of relevant developments and recommend further efforts".
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The European Data Protection Supervisor Giovanni Buttarelli set out the requirement to implement privacy by design in his article.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The European Union Agency for Network and Information Security (ENISA) provided a detailed report *Privacy and Data Protection by Design – From Policy to Engineering* on implementation.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The Summer School on real-world crypto and privacy provided a tutorial on "Engineering Privacy by Design".
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The OWASP Top 10 Privacy Risks Project for web applications that gives hints on how to implement privacy by design in practice.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] The OASIS Privacy by Design Documentation for Software Engineers (PbD-SE) offers a privacy extension/complement to OMG's Unified Modeling Language (UML) and serves as a complement to OASIS’ eXtensible Access Control Mark-up Language (XACML) and Privacy Management Reference Model (PMRM).
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] Privacy by Design guidelines are developed to operationalise some of the high-level privacy-preserving ideas into more granular actionable advice., such as recommendations on how to implement privacy by design into existing (data) systems.
[src:gdpr-compliance/privacy-by-design] However, still the applications of privacy by design guidelines by software developers remains a challenge.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] Pseudonymization (or pseudonymisation, the spelling under European guidelines) is one way to comply with the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) demands for secure data storage of personal information.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] Pseudonymized data can be restored to its original state with the addition of information which allows individuals to be re-identified.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] In contrast, anonymization is intended to prevent re-identification of individuals within the dataset.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] The European Data Protection Supervisor (EDPS) on 9 December 2021 highlighted pseudonymization as the top technical supplementary measure for Schrems II compliance.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] Less than two weeks later, the EU Commission highlighted pseudonymization as an essential element of the equivalency decision for South Korea, which is the status that was lost by the United States under the Schrems II ruling by the Court of Justice of the European Union (CJEU).
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] Protects against unauthorized re-identification via the mosaic effect by generating high entropy (uncertainty) levels by dynamically assigning different tokens at different times for various purposes.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] Before the Schrems II ruling, pseudonymization was a technique used by security experts or government officials to hide personally identifiable information to maintain data structure and privacy of information.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] Some common examples of sensitive information include postal code, location of individuals, names of individuals, race and gender, etc.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] After the Schrems II ruling, GDPR-compliant pseudonymization must satisfy the above-noted elements as an "outcome" versus merely a technique.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] The choice of which data fields are to be pseudonymized is partly subjective.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] Less selective fields, such as birth date or postal code are often also included because they are usually available from other sources and therefore make a record easier to identify.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] Pseudonymizing these less identifying fields removes most of their analytic value and is therefore normally accompanied by the introduction of new derived and less identifying forms, such as year of birth or a larger postal code region.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] Data fields that are less identifying, such as date of attendance, are usually not pseudonymized.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] This is because too much statistical utility is lost in doing so, not because the data cannot be identified.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] For example, given prior knowledge of a few attendance dates it is easy to identify someone's data in a pseudonymized dataset by selecting only those people with that pattern of dates.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] This is an example of an inference attack.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] The weakness of pre-GDPR pseudonymized data to inference attacks is commonly overlooked.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] A famous example is the AOL search data scandal.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] The pseudonym allows tracking back of data to its origins, which distinguishes pseudonymization from anonymization, where all person-related data that could allow backtracking has been purged.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] Pseudonymization is an issue in, for example, patient-related data that has to be passed on securely between clinical centers.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] The application of pseudonymization to e-health intends to preserve the patient's privacy and data confidentiality.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] It allows primary use of medical records by authorized health care providers and privacy preserving secondary use by researchers.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] In the US, HIPAA provides guidelines on how health care data must be handled and data de-identification or pseudonymization is one way to simplify HIPAA compliance.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] However, plain pseudonymization for privacy preservation often reaches its limits when genetic data are involved (see also genetic privacy).
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] Due to the identifying nature of genetic data, depersonalization is often not sufficient to hide the corresponding person.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] Potential solutions are the combination of pseudonymization with fragmentation and encryption.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] Effective as of May 25, 2018, the EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) defines pseudonymization for the very first time at the EU level in Article 4(5).
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] Under Article 4(5) definitional requirements, data is pseudonymized if it cannot be attributed to a specific data subject without the use of separately kept "additional information".
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] Pseudonymized data embodies the state of the art in Data Protection by Design and by Default because it requires protection of both direct and indirect identifiers (not just direct).
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] Because access to separately kept "additional information" is required for re-identification, attribution of data to a specific data subject can be limited by the controller to support lawful purposes only.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] "...implement appropriate technical and organizational measures for ensuring that, by default, only personal data which are necessary for each specific purpose of the processing are processed.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] That obligation applies to the amount of personal data collected, the extent of their processing, the period of their storage and their accessibility.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] A central core of Data Protection by Design and by Default under GDPR Article 25 is enforcement of technology controls that support appropriate uses and the ability to keep promises.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] This trust cannot be maintained using outdated approaches to data protection.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] Pseudonymization, as newly defined under the GDPR, is a means of helping to achieve Data Protection by Design and by Default to earn and maintain trust and more effectively serve businesses, researchers, healthcare providers, and everyone who relies on the integrity of data.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] GDPR-compliant pseudonymization not only enables greater privacy-respectful use of data in the "big data" world of data sharing and combining, but it also enables data controllers and processors to reap explicit benefits under the GDPR for correctly pseudonymized data.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] Article 9(2)(j) with regard to overcoming the general prohibition on processing Article 9(1) special categories of personal data.
[src:gdpr-compliance/pseudonymization] Under Article 20(1), data controllers using Legitimate Interest processing are not subject to the right of portability, which applies only to consent-based processing.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] In general, **compliance** means conforming to a rule, such as a specification, policy, standard or law.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Compliance has traditionally been explained by reference to deterrence theory, according to which punishing a behavior will decrease the violations both by the wrongdoer (specific deterrence) and by others (general deterrence).
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] This view has been supported by economic theory, which has framed punishment in terms of costs and has explained compliance in terms of a cost-benefit equilibrium (Becker 1968).
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] However, psychological research on motivation provides an alternative view: granting rewards (Deci, Koestner and Ryan, 1999) or imposing fines (Gneezy Rustichini 2000) for a certain behavior is a form of extrinsic motivation that weakens intrinsic motivation and ultimately undermines compliance.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Regulations and accrediting organizations vary among fields, with examples such as PCI-DSS and GLBA in the financial industry, FISMA for U.S. federal agencies, HACCP for the food and beverage industry, and the Joint Commission and HIPAA in healthcare.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] In some cases other compliance frameworks (such as COBIT) or even standards (NIST) inform on how to comply with regulations.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Some organizations keep compliance data—all data belonging or pertaining to the enterprise or included in the law, which can be used for the purpose of implementing or validating compliance—in a separate store for meeting reporting requirements.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Compliance software is increasingly being implemented to help companies manage their compliance data more efficiently.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] This store may include calculations, data transfers, and audit trails.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The ISO also produces international standards such as ISO/IEC 27002 to help organizations meet regulatory compliance with their security management and assurance best practices.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Some local or international specialized organizations such as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) also develop standards and regulation codes.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] They thereby provide a wide range of rules and directives to ensure compliance of the products to safety, security or design standards.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance varies not only by industry but often by location.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The financial, research, and pharmaceutical regulatory structures in one country, for example, may be similar but with particularly different nuances in another country.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] These similarities and differences are often a product "of reactions to the changing objectives and requirements in different countries, industries, and policy contexts".
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] These regulators help to ensure financial institutes meet their promises, that transactional information is well documented, and that competition is fair while protecting consumers.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Australian organisations seeking to remain compliant with various regulations may turn to AS ISO 19600:2015 (which supersedes AS 3806-2006).
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] This standard helps organisations with compliance management, placing "emphasis on the organisational elements that are required to support compliance" while also recognizing the need for continual improvement.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] In Canada, federal regulation of deposits, insurance, and superannuation is governed by two independent bodies: the OSFI through the Bank Act, and FINTRAC, mandated by the Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act, 2001 (PCMLTFA).
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] These groups protect consumers, regulate how risk is controlled and managed, and investigate illegal action such as money laundering and terrorist financing.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] On a provincial level, each province maintain individuals laws and agencies.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Unlike any other major federation, Canada does not have a securities regulatory authority at the federal government level.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The provincial and territorial regulators work together to coordinate and harmonize regulation of the Canadian capital markets through the Canadian Securities Administrators (CSA).
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Other key regulators in Canada include the Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA) for food safety, animal health, and plant health; Health Canada for public health; and Environment and Climate Change Canada for environment and sustainable energy.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] For more industry specific guidance, e.g., financial institutions, Canada's E-13 Regulatory Compliance Management provides specific compliance risk management tactics.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance in the European Union (EU) is governed by a harmonized legal framework designed to ensure consistency across member states while allowing for national implementation.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] EU compliance regulations cover various industries, including consumer product safety, financial services, environmental protection, and data privacy.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The General Product Safety Regulation (GPSR) establishes a unified safety framework for consumer products across the EU, requiring manufacturers to conduct risk assessments, maintain traceability documentation, and meet safety compliance standards before placing products on the market.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The GPSR applies to all consumer products made available in the EU unless covered by sector-specific regulations, such as medical devices or food products.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The regulation extends to products sold through e-commerce platforms, requiring online marketplaces to ensure that only compliant products are listed.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Fulfillment service providers are also included as economic operators, making them responsible for product safety compliance in certain cases.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] For business compliance, the EU’s regulatory approach is guided by the New Legislative Framework (NLF) and various sector-specific directives and regulations.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Businesses must comply with EU product conformity assessments and affix the CE marking to indicate compliance with essential safety and performance standards.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Financial compliance is enforced through regulations such as the Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID II) and the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which set strict requirements for financial transparency, consumer protection, and data security.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The EU Legislation Compliance framework ensures that organizations operate within the legal boundaries of EU directives, helping public and private entities manage regulatory risks efficiently.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Companies operating in the EU must stay updated on evolving compliance requirements, as non-compliance can lead to fines, product recalls, or restrictions on market access.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The financial sector in the Netherlands is heavily regulated.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The Dutch Central Bank (De Nederlandsche Bank N.V.) is the prudential regulator while the Netherlands Authority for Financial Markets (AFM) is the regulator for behavioral supervision of financial institutions and markets.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] In India, compliance regulation takes place across three strata: Central, State, and Local regulation.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] India veers towards central regulation, especially of financial organizations and foreign funds.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Compliance regulations vary based on the industry segment in addition to the geographical mix.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Most regulation comes in the following broad categories: economic regulation, regulation in the public interest, and environmental regulation.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] India has also been characterized by poor compliance - reports suggest that only around 65% of companies are fully compliant to norms.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The Monetary Authority of Singapore is Singapore's central bank and financial regulatory authority.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] It administers the various statutes pertaining to money, banking, insurance, securities and the financial sector in general, as well as currency issuance.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] There is considerable regulation in the United Kingdom, some of which is derived from European Union legislation.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Various areas are policed by different bodies, such as the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), Environment Agency, Scottish Environment Protection Agency, Information Commissioner's Office, Care Quality Commission, and others: see List of regulators in the United Kingdom.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Important compliance issues for all organizations large and small include the Data Protection Act 2018 and, for the public sector, Freedom of Information Act 2000.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Corporate scandals and breakdowns such as the Enron case of reputational risk in 2001 have increased calls for stronger compliance and regulations, particularly for publicly listed companies.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) is an agency of the United States Department of the Treasury under the auspices of the Under Secretary of the Treasury for Terrorism and Financial Intelligence.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] OFAC administers and enforces economic and trade sanctions based on U.S. foreign policy and national security goals against targeted foreign states, organizations, and individuals.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in the U.S. generally means compliance with laws and regulations.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] These laws and regulations can have criminal or civil penalties.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The definition of what constitutes an effective compliance plan has been elusive.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Most authors, however, continue to cite the guidance provided by the United States Sentencing Commission in Chapter 8 of the Federal Sentencing Guidelines.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Small Business Administration re-launched Business.gov (later Business.USA.gov and finally SBA.Gov) which provides a single point of access to government services and information that help businesses comply with government regulations.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Department of Labor, Occupational Health and Safety Administration (OSHA) was created by Congress to assure safe and healthful working conditions for working men and women by setting and enforcing standards and by providing training, outreach, education, and assistance.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] OSHA implements laws and regulations regularly in the following areas, construction, maritime, agriculture, and recordkeeping.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The United States Department of Transportation also has various laws and regulations requiring that prime contractors when bidding on federally funded projects engage in good faith effort compliance, meaning they must document their outreach to certified disadvantaged business enterprises.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Data retention is a part of regulatory compliance that is proving to be a challenge in many instances.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The security that comes from compliance with industry regulations can seem contrary to maintaining user privacy.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Data retention laws and regulations ask data owners and other service providers to retain extensive records of user activity beyond the time necessary for normal business operations.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] These requirements have been called into question by privacy rights advocates.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in this area is becoming very difficult.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Laws like the CAN-SPAM Act and Fair Credit Reporting Act in the U.S. require that businesses give people the right to be forgotten.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] In other words, they must remove individuals from marketing lists if it is requested, tell them when and why they might share personal information with a third party, or at least ask permission before sharing that data.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Now, with new laws coming out that demand longer data retention despite the individual’s desires, it can create some real difficulties.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Money laundering and terrorist financing pose significant threats to the integrity of the financial system and national security.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] To combat these threats, the EU has adopted a risk-based approach to Anti-Money Laundering and Combating the Financing of Terrorism (AML/CFT) that relies on cooperation and coordination between EU and national authorities.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] In this context, risk-based regulation refers to the approach of identifying and assessing potential risks of money laundering and terrorist financing and implementing regulatory measures proportional to those risks.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] However, the shared enforcement powers between EU and national authorities in the implementation and enforcement of AML/CFT regulations can create legal implications and challenges.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The potential for inconsistent application of AML regulations across different jurisdictions can create regulatory arbitrage and undermine the effectiveness of AML efforts.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Additionally, a lack of clear and consistent legal frameworks defining the roles and responsibilities of EU and national authorities in AML enforcement can lead to situations where accountability is difficult to establish.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Corporate Governance Code (formerly the Combined Code) is issued by the Financial Reporting Council (FRC) and "sets standards of good practice in relation to board leadership and effectiveness, remuneration, accountability, and relations with shareholders".
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] All companies with a Premium Listing of equity shares in the U.K. are required under the Listing Rules to report on how they have applied the Combined Code in their annual report and accounts.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] It further demonstrates the relationship that subsists among shareholders, management, and the independent audit teams.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Financial statements must be prepared using a particular set of rules and regulations hence the rationale behind allowing the companies to apply the provisions of company law, international financial reporting standards (IFRS), as well as the U.K. stock exchange rules as directed by the FCA.
[src:gdpr-compliance/regulatory-compliance] It is also possible that shareholders may not understand the figures as presented in the various financial statements, hence it is critical that the board should provide notes on accounting policies as well as other explanatory notes to help them understand the report better.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The **right to be forgotten** (**RTBF**) is the right to have private information about a person removed from Internet searches and other directories in some circumstances.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The issue arose from the desires of individuals to "determine the development of their life in an autonomous way, without being perpetually or periodically stigmatized as a consequence of a specific action performed in the past".
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The right entitles a person to have data about them deleted so that it can no longer be discovered by third parties, particularly through search engines.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Those who favor a right to be forgotten cite its necessity due to issues such as revenge porn sites and references to past petty crimes appearing in search engine listings for a person's name.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The main concern is for the potentially undue influence that such results may exert upon a person's online reputation indefinitely if not removed.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Those who oppose the right worry about its effect on the right to freedom of expression and whether creating a right to be forgotten would result in a decreased quality of the Internet, censorship, and the rewriting of history.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The right to be forgotten is distinct from the right to privacy.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The right to privacy constitutes information that is not known publicly, whereas the right to be forgotten involves revoking public access to information that was known publicly at a certain time.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Argentina has had lawsuits by celebrities against Google and Yahoo! in which the plaintiffs demand the removal of certain search results, and require removal of links to photographs.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] One case, brought by artist Virginia da Cunha, involved photographs which had originally been taken with her permission and uploaded with her permission, however she alleged that the search results improperly associated her photographs with pornography.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Da Cunha's case achieved initial success resulting in Argentina search engines not showing images of the particular celebrity, however, this decision is on appeal.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Virginia Simari, the judge in favor of Da Cunha, stated that people have the right to control their image and avert others from "capturing, reproducing, broadcasting, or publishing one's image without permission".
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Argentina's efforts to protect their people's right to be forgotten has been called "the most complete" because individuals are able to correct, delete, or update information about themselves: overall, their information is bound to remain confidential.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In 2016, a Chinese court in Beijing rejected an argument for the right to be forgotten when a judge ruled in favor of Baidu in a lawsuit over removing search results.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] It was the first of such cases to be heard in Chinese court.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In the suit, Ren Jiayu sued Chinese search engine Baidu over search results that negatively associated him with a previous employer, Wuxi Taoshi Biotechnology.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Ren argued that by posting the search results, Baidu had infringed upon his right of name and right of reputation, both protected under Chinese law.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Because of these protections, Ren believed he had a right to be forgotten by removing these search results.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The court ruled against Ren, claiming his name is a collection of common characters and as a result the search results were derived from relevant words.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The court described search results as neutral findings based on an algorithm and stated that retaining such information was necessary for the public.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] As the call for personal information protection has grown louder, China has taken active measures to strengthen data protection.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In 2018, China released the national standard "Information Security Technology—Personal Information Security Specification," which was the first systematic regulation for personal information protection.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In 2020, the updated national standards replaced the version that came into effect in 2018.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Subsequently, in 2021, China introduced the formal legal framework, the "Personal Information Protection Law of the People's Republic of China" (PIPL).
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The enactment of this law filled a legal gap and made detailed provisions regarding the collection, storage, use, transfer, and deletion of personal information.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] For businesses, it is essential to follow the principles of legality, fairness, and necessity when collecting and using personal data, ensuring transparency and data security.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Moreover, the PIPL strengthens the regulation of cross-border data flows, requiring risk assessments in specific cases and mandating additional protective measures for users.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Europe's data protection laws do not implement a "right to be forgotten", but a more limited "right to [data] erasure".
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Although the term "right to be forgotten" is a relatively new idea, the European Court of Justice legally solidified that the "right to be forgotten" is a human right when they ruled against Google in the *Costeja* case on May 13, 2014.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] This raises questions about the limitations of application in a jurisdiction include the inability to require removal of information possessed by companies outside the jurisdiction.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] There is no global framework to allow individuals control over their online image.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In 1995, the European Union adopted the European Data Protection Directive (Directive 95/46/EC) to regulate the processing of personal data.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Data protection is now considered a component of human rights law.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), in force since 2018, provides protection and exemption for companies listed as "media" companies, like newspapers and other journalistic work.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] However, Google purposely opted out of being classified as a "media" company, therefore the company is not protected.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Judges in the European Union ruled that because the international corporation, Google, is a collector and processor of data it should be classified as a "data controller" under the meaning of the EU data protection directive.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] These "data controllers" are required under EU law to remove data that is "inadequate, irrelevant, or no longer relevant", making this directive of global importance.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In Article 12 of the Directive 95/46/EC the EU gave a legal basis to Internet protection for individuals.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] A *right to be forgotten* was replaced by a more limited *right of erasure* in Article 17 of the GDPR, which came into force in May 2018.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] To exercise the right to be forgotten and request removal from a search engine, one must complete a form through the search engine's website.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Google's removal request process requires the applicant to identify their country of residence, personal information, a list of the URLs to be removed along with a short description, and – in some cases – attachment of legal identification.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The applicant receives an email from Google confirming the request but the request must be assessed before it is approved for removal.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] If the request is approved, searches using the individual's name will no longer result in the content appearing in search results.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The content remains online and is not erased.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] After a request is filled, their removals team reviews the request, weighing "the individual's right to privacy against the public's right to know", deciding if the website is "inadequate, irrelevant or no longer relevant, or excessive in relation to the purposes for which they were processed".
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Google has formed an Advisory Council of various professors, lawyers, and government officials from around Europe to provide guidelines for these decisions.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] However, the review process is still a mystery to the general public.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Guidelines set by EU regulators were not released until November 2014, but Google began to take action on this much sooner than that, which (according to one author) allowed them "to shape interpretation to [their] own ends".
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In May 2015, eighty academics called for more transparency from Google in an open letter.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The form asks people to select one of the 27 countries that make up the European Union, as well as Andorra, Iceland, Liechtenstein, Monaco, Norway, San Marino, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom, plus several dependent territories.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] "The form allows an individual or someone representing an individual to put in a request" for the removal of any URLs believed to be a violation of the individual's privacy.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Regardless of who is submitting the form, some form of photo identification of the person the form is being submitted for must be present.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] This is meant to serve as proof that the person for whom the request was made for does in fact approve.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] If Google refuses a request to delink material, Europeans can appeal to their local data protection agency.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] As of May 2015, the British Information Commissioner's Office (ICO) had treated 184 such complaints, and overturned Google's decision in about a quarter of those.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] If Google fails to comply with a decision of the ICO, it can face legal action.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Google indeed acknowledged that some of its search result removals, affecting articles that were of public interest, were incorrect, and reinstated the links a week later.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Google notifies websites that have URLs delinked, and various news organizations, such as BBC, have published lists of delinked articles.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Complainants have been named in news commentary regarding those delinkings.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In August 2015 the ICO issued an enforcement action requiring Google to delink some of these more recent articles from searches for a complainant's name, after Google refused to do so.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Some academics have criticized news organizations and Google for their behavior.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In July 2015, Google accidentally revealed data on delinkings that "shows 95% of Google privacy requests are from citizens out to protect personal and private information – not criminals, politicians and public figures." Only 5% of requests were made by criminals, politicians, and public figures.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] One request for data removal was from a British doctor requesting to have 50 links removed on past botched medical procedures.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Google agreed to remove three search results containing his personal information.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The European Union has been advocating for the delinkings requested by EU citizens to be implemented by Google not just in European versions of Google (as in google.co.uk, google.fr, etc.), but on google.com and other international subdomains.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Regulators want delinkings to be implemented so that the law cannot be circumvented in any way.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Google has refused the French Data Protection Agency's demand to apply the right internationally.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Due in part to their refusal to comply with the recommendation of the privacy regulating board Google has become the subject of a four-year-long antitrust investigation by the European Commission.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In September 2015, the French Data Protection Agency dismissed Google's appeal.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The French Data Protection Agency appealed to the EU courts to seek action on Google for failing to delink in its global servers.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] As of September 2015, the most delinked site is *www.facebook.com*.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Three of Google's own sites, *groups.google.com*, *plus.google.com* and *www.youtube.com* are among the ten most delinked sites.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In addition to Google, Yahoo! and Bing have also made forms available for making delinking requests.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In September 2019, the European Court of Justice ruled that the right to be forgotten did not apply outside of its member states.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The ruling meant that Google did not have to delete the names of individuals from all of its international versions.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] They do not however need to obtain explicit consent before indexing such data, even though the law typically requires explicit consent before data processing, on the basis that such examination would not be within the powers, responsibiities or capabilities of a search engine.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The consequences of this judgment have been criticised in data protection scholarship, as its logic implies that technologies that are designed in a way that renders data protection compliance impossible may be given the right to avoid the law.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In December 2022, the judges in Luxembourg further extended the right to be forgotten in the case C-460/20 *TU, RE v Google LLC*.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The case related to two managers of a group of investment companies, who argued that three unflattering news articles should be 'de-referenced' from the search engine results of Google, when searching for their names.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] They claimed that the information presented in the articles was wrong factually, which raised the question whether search engine operators need to check the accuracy of the information.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Additionally, the applicants required that photographs showing them in preview images – or thumbnails – when carrying out a search ought to be removed.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In this judgment the European Court of Justice largely agreed with the request of the applicants.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Search engine operators such as Google are required to de-reference the respective information, if a person who seeks de-referencing submits 'relevant and sufficient' evidence capable of substantiating his or her request, and thereby manifests the inaccuracy of the information found (para.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] For thumbnails an independent assessment must be performed, but essentially the same thinking applies.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Europe's jurisdiction of data also extends beyond its borders into countries that does not have "adequate" protections.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] For instance, Europe's transfer of data to vulnerable countries are limited, resulting in companies like Google and Amazon establishing European data centers to quarantine data from Europe.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] He initially attempted to have the article removed by complaining to the Spanish Data Protection Agency, which rejected the claim on the grounds that it was lawful and accurate, but accepted a complaint against Google and asked Google to remove the results.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Google sued in the Spanish *Audiencia Nacional* (National High Court) which referred a series of questions to the European Court of Justice.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The court ruled that search engines are responsible for the content they point to and thus, Google was required to comply with EU data privacy laws.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] On its first day of compliance only (May 30, 2014), Google received 12,000 requests to have personal details removed from its search engine.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Stopp, attorney for Werlé and Lauber, had won a default judgment in German court, on behalf of Lauber, against the Wikimedia Foundation.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] According to the Electronic Frontier Foundation, Werlé's lawyers also challenged an Internet service provider in Austria which published the names of the convicted killers.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Wikimedia is based in the United States, where the First Amendment protects freedom of speech and freedom of the press.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In Germany, the law seeks to protect the name and likenesses of private persons from unwanted publicity.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] On January 18, 2008, a court in Hamburg supported the personality rights of Werlé, which by German law includes removing his name from archive coverage of the case.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] On November 12, 2009, *The New York Times* reported that Wolfgang Werlé had a case pending against the Wikimedia Foundation in a German court.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The editors of the German-language Wikipedia article about Sedlmayr removed the names of the murderers, which have since then been restored to the article.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] *The Guardian* observed that the lawsuit has resulted in the Streisand effect, an upsurge in publicity for the case resulting from the legal action.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] On December 15, 2009, the German Federal Court of Justice (*Bundesgerichtshof*) in Karlsruhe ruled that German websites do not have to check their archives in order to provide permanent protection of personality rights for convicted criminals.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The case occurred after the names of the brothers were found on the website of *Deutschlandradio*, in an archive article dating from July 2000.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The presiding judge Gregor Galke stated "This is not a blank check", and stated that the right to rehabilitation of offenders had been taken into consideration.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] On November 28, 2019, the federal constitutional court in Karlsruhe ruled that German murderer Paul Termann had the right to be forgotten.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The 2012 draft European Data Protection Regulation Article 17 detailed the "right to be forgotten and to erasure".
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The EU defines "data controllers" as "people or bodies that collect and manage personal data".
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Where the controller has authorized a third party publication of personal data, the controller shall be considered responsible for that publication".
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In the situation that a data controller does not take all reasonable steps then they will be fined heavily.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The European Parliament was once "expected to adopt the proposals in first reading in the April 2013 Plenary session".
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The right to be forgotten was replaced by a more limited right to erasure in the version of the GDPR adopted by the European Parliament in March 2014.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The European Union is an influential group of states, and this tendency towards the right to be forgotten in the EU is an indicator of its recognition globally as a right.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] To support this, in 2012 the Obama Administration released a "Privacy Bill of Rights" to protect consumers online.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In June 2014, Privacy Commissioner Allan Chiang Yam-wang (蔣任宏) expressed his support for introducing the right to be forgotten to Hong Kong.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Opposition expressed their worry that the right would inhibit freedom of information, and introducing erase from history.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Charles Mok, Hong Kong Legislative Councillor from I.T. occupation, oppose to introduce the right to be forgotten, citing the difficulty of enforcing and abuses of practising the right.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] He described the abuses as "right to be deleteion" In July 2015, Stephen Wong Kai-yi (黃繼兒) replaced Chiang's position and promised not to introduce the right to be forgotten.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In April 2016, the Delhi High Court began to examine the issue after a Delhi banker requested to have his personal details removed from search results after a marital dispute.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In this case, due to the dispute being settled, the banker's request is valid.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The High Court has asked for a reply from Google and other search engine companies by September 19, upon which the court will continue to investigate the issue.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In January 2017, the Karnataka High Court upheld the right to be forgotten, in a case involving a woman who originally went to court in order to get a marriage certificate annulled, claiming to have never been married to the man on the certificate.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] After the two parties came to an agreement, the woman's father wanted her name to be removed from search engines regarding criminal cases in the high court.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The Karnataka High Court approved the father's request, stating that she had a right to be forgotten.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] As of February 2017, the Delhi High Court is hearing a case involving a man requesting to have information regarding his mother and wife to be removed from a search engine.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The man believes that having his name linked to the search is hindering his employment options.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The Delhi High Court is still working on the case, along with the issue of whether or not a right to be forgotten should be a legal standard in India.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Currently, there is no legal standard for the right to be forgotten, but if implemented, this would mean that citizens no longer need to file a case in order to request for information from search engines to be removed.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] This case could have significant impacts on the right to be forgotten and search engines in India.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In May 2016, South Korea's Communications Commission (KCC) announced citizens will be able to request search engines and website administrators to restrict their own postings from being accessible publicly.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The KCC released "Guidelines on the Right to Request Access Restrictions on Personal Internet Postings", which took effect in June 2016 and do not apply to third party contents.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] To the extent that the right to be forgotten concerns a data subject's right to limit the searchability of third party postings about him/her, the Guideline does not constitute a right to be forgotten.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The guidelines created by the KCC include that data subjects can remove content that includes the URL links, and any evidence consisting of personal information.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The commission included different amendments to the guideline.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] This includes describing the Guidelines as a "minimum" and "preliminary" precaution regarding privacy rights in vague areas of existing laws.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The guideline encompasses foreign Internet companies that provide translation services for South Korean consumers.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In order to have a person's information "forgotten" he or she has to go through a three step process: the issue posted with the URL, proof of ownership of the post, grounds for the request.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] When posting the URL, the web operator has the right to preserve the posting issue.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The second being that if the post is relevant to public interest, web operators will process this request on the terms of relevance.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The right to be forgotten was added in the constitution of the Canton of Geneva in the new article 21A *right to digital integrity* voted on June 18, 2023.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Consideration of the right to be forgotten occurred in US case law, specifically in *Melvin v.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Reid* (1931), an ex-prostitute was charged with murder and then acquitted; she subsequently tried to assume a quiet and anonymous place in society.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] However, the 1925 movie *The Red Kimono* revealed her history, and she successfully sued the producer.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] FR Publishing Corp.* (1940), the plaintiff, William James Sidis, was a former child prodigy who wished to spend his adult life quietly, without recognition; however, this was disrupted by an article in *The New Yorker*.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The court held here that there were limits to the right to control one's life and facts about oneself, and held that there is social value in published facts, and that a person cannot ignore their celebrity status merely because they want to.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] These criticisms are consistent with the proposal that the only information that can be removed by user's request is content that they themselves uploaded.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In a June 2014 opinion piece in *Forbes*, columnist Joseph Steinberg noted that "many privacy protections that Americans believe that they enjoy – even some guaranteed by law – have, in fact, been eroded or even obliterated by technological advances".
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] On March 11, 2015, Intelligence Squared US, an organization that stages Oxford-Style debates, held an event concerning the question, "Should the U.S. adopt the 'Right to be Forgotten' online?" The side against the motion won with a 56% majority of the voting audience.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] While opinions among experts are divided in the U.S., one survey indicated that 9 in 10 Americans want some form of the right to be forgotten.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The consumer rights organization Consumer Watchdog has filed a complaint with the Federal Trade Commission for Americans to obtain the right as well.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In June 2018, California enacted the California Consumer Privacy Act, providing consumers with the right to delete their personal information from covered businesses.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In October 2023, the state enacted the California Delete Act, requiring the California Privacy Protection Agency to establish a one-stop shop deletion mechanism for consumers to direct data brokers to delete their personal information.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In January 2021, the *Boston Globe* announced a program to allow subjects of relatively inconsequential stories to have the stories contextualized, removed from Google searches or anonymized.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In January 2025, it was reported that *The Oregonian, The Plain Dealer, Bangor Daily News, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution* and NJ.com offered similar services.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The regulatory differences in the protection of personal data between countries has real impact on international relations.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The right to be forgotten, specifically, is a matter of EU-US relations when applied to cross-border data flow, as it raises questions about territorial sovereignty.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The structure of the Westphalian international system assumes that the reach of a country's jurisdiction is limited to its geographic territory.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] However, online interactions are independent of geographic location and present across multiple locations, rendering the traditional concept of territorial sovereignty moot.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Therefore, the EU and the United States are forced to confront their regulatory differences and negotiate on a set of regulations that apply to all foreign companies processing and handling data of European citizens and residents.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The regulatory differences on the right to be forgotten along with numerous other data protection rights have affected discussions and negotiations on trans-Atlantic data privacy regulations.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] A case in point is the EU and the United States' endeavors to develop the International Safe Harbor Privacy Principles agreement, a data transfer pact that enables the transfer of data between the EU and US companies in a manner consistent with the EU's data protection schemes.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Article 25 of the Data Protection Directive articulates that cross-border transfer of data can take place only if the "third country in question ensures an adequate level of protection," meaning that the country meets the EU's minimum standards of data protection.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The standards include, among many provisions, a component that protects the right to "opt out" of further processing or transmission of personal data, with the assumption that data may not be further processed in ways inconsistent with the intent for which they were collected.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Given the inconsistencies between the EU and the United States on numerous digital privacy regulations, including the right to be forgotten, Article 25 poses a threat to trans-Atlantic data flows.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] As a result of the mass surveillance performed by the US government on European citizens' data, the Safe Harbor agreement has been invalidated by the European Union Court of Justice in its *Schrems* case.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The Safe Harbor agreement has now been replaced by the Privacy Shield principles.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Businesses that manage their clients' online reputations have responded to the European Court ruling by exercising the right to be forgotten as a means to remove unfavorable information.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] One technique used by reputation consulting companies is to submit multiple requests for each link, written with different angles in an attempt to get links removed.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Google, for example, does not limit the number of requests that can be submitted on the removal of a given link.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Major criticisms stem from the idea that the right to be forgotten would restrict the right to freedom of speech.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Many nations, and the United States in particular (with the First Amendment to the United States Constitution), have very strong domestic freedom of speech laws, which would be challenging to reconcile with the right to be forgotten.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Some academics see that only a limited form of the right to be forgotten would be reconcilable with US constitutional law; the right of an individual to delete data that they have personally submitted.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In this limited form of the right individuals could not have material removed that has been uploaded by others, as demanding the removal of information could constitute censorship and a reduction in the freedom of expression in many countries.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Sandra Coliver of the Open Society Justice Initiative argues that not all rights must be compatible and this conflict between the two rights is not detrimental to the survival of either.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The draft General Data Protection Regulation was written broadly and this has caused concern.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] It has attracted criticism that its enactment would require data controlling companies to go to great lengths to identify third parties with the information and remove it.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In addition to this, there are concerns about the requirement to take down information that others have posted about an individual; the definition of personal data in Article 4(2) includes "any information relating to" the individual.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] This, critics have claimed, would require companies to take down any information relating to an individual, regardless of its source, which would amount to censorship, and result in the big data companies eradicating much data to comply with this.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Such removal can impact the accuracy and ability of businesses and individuals to perform business intelligence, particularly due diligence to comply with anti bribery, anticorruption, and know your customer laws.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Other criticism revolves around the principle of accountability.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] There were concerns that the proposed General Data Protection Regulation would result in Google and other Internet search engines not producing neutral search results, but rather producing biased and patchy results, and compromising the integrity of Internet-based information.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Despite these criticisms and Google's action, the company's CEO, Larry Page worries that the ruling will be "used by other governments that aren't as forward and progressive as Europe to do bad things", though has since distanced himself from that statement.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] For example, pianist Dejan Lazic cited the "Right To Be Forgotten" in trying to remove a negative review about his performance from *The Washington Post*.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] He claimed that the critique was "defamatory, mean-spirited, opinionated, offensive and simply irrelevant for the arts". and the St.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Lawrence parish of the Roman Catholic church in Kutno, Poland asked Google to remove the Polish Wikipedia page about it, (in Polish) without any allegations mentioned therein as of that date.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Index on Censorship claimed that the *Costeja* ruling "allows individuals to complain to search engines about information they do not like with no legal oversight.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] This is akin to marching into a library and forcing it to pulp books.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Although the ruling is intended for private individuals it opens the door to anyone who wants to whitewash their personal history… The Court's decision is a retrograde move that misunderstands the role and responsibility of search engines and the wider Internet.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In 2014, the Gerry Hutch page on the English Wikipedia was among the first Wikipedia pages to be removed by several search engines' query results in the European Union.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] *The Daily Telegraph* said, on 6 August 2014, that Wikipedia co-founder Jimmy Wales "described the EU's Right to be Forgotten as deeply immoral, as the organisation that operates the online encyclopedia warned the ruling will result in an Internet riddled with memory holes".
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Other commentators have disagreed with Wales, pointing to problems such as Google including links to revenge porn sites in its search results, and have accused Google of orchestrating a publicity campaign to escape the burdensome obligation to comply with the law.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In response to the criticism, the EU has released a factsheet to address what it considers myths about the right to be forgotten.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In addition to this, for further clarification of the law, the factsheet provides information about the important court case C-131/12 and frequently asked questions regarding Google, the purpose of the law, and how it works.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Other criticisms involving the right to be forgotten concerns the policies for data removal regarding minors.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The U.S. has laws that protect the privacy of minors.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The California Minor Eraser Law is a law that allows California residents younger than the age of 18 to request to have information removed that they posted on an online server.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The law "applies to websites, social media sites, mobile apps and other online services" and follows "Europe's recognition of the 'right to be forgotten'".
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] This law became effective on January 1, 2015 and remains in existence.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Online "service" operators that have services "directed toward minors" must update their privacy policies to include the option to remove data if requested by a minor that is posted on a service.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In the UK, the 2017 Conservative manifesto included a pledge to allow social media platform users to remove outdated information that was posted when they were younger than the age of 18.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] "A Tory victory on the 8th of June will lead to those youthful indiscretions on Facebook and Twitter being open to erasure.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] But there are also plans to fine social media firms for not moving at the speed of political opportunism over extreme content." The United Kingdom has not yet fully adopted the ruling of the European Court of Justice regarding the right to be forgotten and argued to keep it from becoming EU law.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] However, in the upcoming elections in the UK laws could be passed to allow minors to remove embarrassing posts or photos on social media that could come back to affect job applications or public image in later life.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Theresa May, then Prime Minister of the UK, has advocated to extend privacy rights for minors in allowing them to have a right to delete information.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The intentions for this extension of privacy are based on the fact that social media sites store years of data that affect minors lives' much later after the information is posted.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] May gave her stance on privacy when she said, "'The Internet has brought a wealth of opportunity but also significant new risks which have evolved faster than society's response to them'".
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The Conservative Party, which was headed by May from 2016 to 2019, has pushed for policies that aggressively remove illegal material from the Internet and fine firms that do not take action in removing said material.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] In 2015, Commission nationale de l'informatique et des libertés (CNIL) asked Google to remove data from all versions available in any part of the world.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Google and other entities argued that European data regulators should not be allowed to decide what Internet users around the world find when they use a search engine.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Security researchers from CISPA, Saarland University and the University of Auckland are working to develop software to support the automation of the right to be forgotten in a scalable, provable and privacy-preserving manner.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The team's software, Oblivion, would automate the process of verifying someone's personal information can be found in a Google search result, to help Google staff manage the high volume of take-down requests.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Researchers have noted that the current capabilities of this technology have some limitations.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] The software can only determine whether a piece of information is available, not whether it should be removed.
[src:gdpr-compliance/right-to-be-forgotten] Data deletion protocols concerning the death of a user is another consideration.
